            I am not aware of the kind of conditions in which people are held within all the jurisdictions that will be covered by Part 1. However, they will vary
            
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_185gc' title='Col. 185GC &mdash; HL Deb 01 July 2003 vol 650 c185GC' name='column_185gc' href='#column_185gc' rel='bookmark'>185GC</a>
            considerably: some will be more allied to remand conditions, which, although extremely unpleasant, are certainly not the same as being held in prison on a sentence. As I understand it, in other jurisdictions conditions will be far more allied to those that we have here when serving a sentence. The noble and learned Lord, Lord Donaldson, has tabled a very interesting point.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0650P0-04534'>
        <a name='S5LV0650P0_20030701_GCR_105'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-william-goodhart' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0650P0_20030701_GCR_105' title='Link to this speech by Mr William Goodhart' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
